        (150, 'Nio (NYSE:NIO) reports monthly record deliveries of 7,007 units (+121% Y/Y) in December, ending FY20 with 43,728 units, up 113% Y/Y. The company has achieved stellar growth in 2020 despite the pandemic year. The company delivered 17,353 vehicles in Q4, up 111.0% Y/Y, above the top end of the company''s own guidance. Dec. delivery by model: ES8s - 2009, ES6s - 2,493 and EC6sd - 2,505. As of December 31, 2020, cumulative deliveries of the ES8, ES6 and EC6 reached 75,641 vehicles. “These results are attributable to the growing recognition of our premium brand, the competitive and compelling products and services, the expanding sales network, and most importantly, the continuous support from our passionate and loyal user community," said William Bin Li CEO. The company plans to reveal new sedan model and share the latest development of autonomous driving and other core technologies on the fourth NIO Day scheduled on January 9th. Tesla falls just short of 500K deliveries in 2020.'),
        (151, 'The one thing that bank investors can expect in 2021 is the return of stock buybacks after the Fed eased restrictions on capital returns. Evercore ISI analyst Glenn Schorr sees trust banks and brokers with the "most firepower" for buybacks. M&T Bank (NYSE:MTB), which fared the worst in the Fed''s stress scenarios, is unlikely to to resume share repurchases, he wrote. Still, some banks may elect to delay buybacks due to their view of economic and credit conditions. Analysts also see a weaker dollar and gradual increase in long-term Treasury yields, both of which can benefit banks. To be sure, bank investors are likely eager to bid 2020 farewell. S&P 500 Bank index declined 17% (orange line in chart below) during the year, while the broader S&P 500 gained 18% (blue). Regional banks (purple) didn''t fall as much as the big banks, declining 8% for the year. But for the big diversified banks there were some very bright spots — capital markets and mortgage banking to name two. In addition, M&A activity roared back in H2. While none of the following financial sectors outperformed the S&P 500 (light blue line) in 2020, the S&P 500 Financial Exchanges and Data Index (green) came the closest followed by the S&P 500 Capital Markets Index (purple). The others in the chart: S&P Global Listed Private Equity Index (red), S&P 1500 Composite Consumer Finance Index (dark blue), and S&P 500 Banks Index (orange): Indeed, the only U.S. megabank stock that exceeded the S&P 500''s performance during the past year was Morgan Stanley (NYSE:MS) (rising 38%), which doesn''t take deposits like a traditional bank. Rather, it makes its money from capital markets operations, wealth management services, and sales and trading. For most of 2020, JPMorgan analyst Kabir Caprihan favored brokers over banks. Now he favors diversified money-center banks, "reflecting current spread levels and improved macroeconomic projections." And with Morgan Stanley''s rally vs. other banks and the S&P 500, Caprihan downgraded the stock to Neutral from Overweight in mid-December. Conversely, he upgraded Wells Fargo (NYSE:WFC). Morgan Stanley''s Betsy Graseck sees COVID vaccinations, the new fiscal stimulus and a potential service economy rebound helping banks next year and bank credit losses should continue to decline. Rising earnings should boost stock buybacks into H2 2021. She upgraded large-cap banks and consumer finance sectors to Attractive from In-Line in late November. KBW analysts Frederick Cannon and Brian Kleinhanzl see financial stocks as well-poised for outperformance in 2021 assuming the fiscal stimulus isn''t "too modest." They also see lending expanding in 2021, through both banks and non-banks. A weaker dollar signals that the "worst of deflation fears" have eased, Kleinhanzl wrote. He upgraded the universal bank sector to Overweight earlier this month, citing potential earnings catalysts of credit recovery, buybacks and a better macro environment. See how the six big banks stack up in Quant factor grades: Mortgage banking will face tougher comparisons next year after 2020''s gangbuster performance, according to Jefferies analyst Ken Usdin, though he still sees strong production in 2021. "Elevated prepayment activity (seen in MBS prepay speeds) due to strong refi activity is weighing on NII (via higher prem. amortization) and mort. servicing fees today, but these burdens should lessen looking ahead," he wrote. Certainly, investors will get a better sense of 2021 activity when banks start reporting Q4 2020 earnings in mid-January. Odeon Capital analyst Dick Bove offers several reasons why bank earnings may surprise to the upside — strength in capital markets, strong deposit flows, higher interest rates at the long end of the curve, and loan losses are likely to be stable. Risks include: declining commercial and industrial loan volume; slower residential lending; and the end of forbearance on debt in some categories may lead to increased loan losses, Bove wrote. In addition, many regional banks may need to boost spending on technology and most regionals aren''t involved in capital markets activity, he added. Screen diversified bank stocks (market cap >$2B) by Quant rating. Stone Fox Capital calls Wells Fargo stock "extremely cheap" and points to the bank''s path to normalized EPS of $6-$8, helped by cost cuts and stock buybacks.'),
        (152, 'While the S&P 500 gained 18% in 2020 even with the pressures of the pandemic, most of the gains came from a handful of humongous tech companies. You recognize the names — Apple, Microsoft, Amazon, Nvidia — that have dominated the stock movers headlines. But as COVID-19 vaccines roll out, the market should continue to broaden as investors shift their focus on company fundamentals, writes Janus Henderson portfolio manager Jonathan Coleman. Specifically, he sees optimism for small and mid-cap equities in 2021 because the disconnect between stock performance and company fundamentals that occurred in 2020 isn''t sustainable, Coleman contends. During 2020, the stocks of money-losing companies outperformed the stocks of those that made money by a ratio of two to one, with a similar dynamic occurring in mid-cap stocks, he said. Part of that resulted from investors focusing on stocks that they believed might benefit from the pandemic, even if they continued to lose money. They also avoided stocks that they thought might see near-term earnings damage from COVID-19 and ignored their longer-term growth potential. The resurgence of individual investors trading on low-cost investment platforms like Robinhoood "exacerbated momentum-driven, rather than fundamentals-driven, moves" in parts of the equity markets, Coleman writes. "In the third quarter we saw signs this dynamic may be shifting, as profitable, moderately valued companies performed better on a relative basis even if they still lagged the broader market," he said. He expects a greater focus on fundamentals on a wider range of companies with sustainable revenue and earnings growth potential. Investors should look for companies with "strong and durable competitive advantages, high returns on invested capital and strong free cash flows." In a post-COVID world, consumers will continue to embrace online shopping and e-commerce is likely to grow as a share of total consumer spending, Coleman writes. While it may not be reflected in near-term stock prices, companies that innovate to adapt to the new post-COVID environment should ultimately be rewarded by investors, he said. Vanguard Mid-Cap Value ETF (NYSEARCA:VOE) lags the S&P 500 during 2020, while Vanguard Mid-Cap Growth ETF (NYSEARCA:VOT) outperform. Will that turn around in 2021? The Sunday Investor sees the trend of growth stocks outperforming starting to reverse. Small-, mid-cap growth ETFs: VBK, VOT, IWO, FFTY, IJT, IWP Small-, mid-cap value ETFs: VBR, IJS, RVT, VOE, IWN, SLYV'),
